        {
            "id": "DJN_DN20250824000568:0",
            "title": "Tourism Holdings Swings to Annual Loss on Impairments",
            "description": "<div class=\"body-KX2tCBZq body-pIO_GYwT content-pIO_GYwT\"><div class=\"symbolsContainer-cBh_FN2P logosContainer-cwMMKgmm\" data-no-swipe=\"true\"></div><div><span><p class=\"\"><strong class=\"root-Tkn6WL2y\"><span>(20:39 GMT) </span></strong><span>*Tourism Holdings FY Net Loss NZ$25.8 Million</span><br/><strong class=\"root-Tkn6WL2y\"><span>(20:39 GMT) </span></strong><span>*Tourism Holdings FY Revenue NZ$937.2 Million, Up 2%</span><br/><strong class=\"root-Tkn6WL2y\"><span>(20:40 GMT) </span></strong><span>*Tourism Holdings Final Dividend 4 New Zealand Cents/Security</span><br/><strong class=\"root-Tkn6WL2y\"><span>(20:40 GMT) </span></strong><span>*Tourism Holdings FY Underlying Net Profit NZ$28.7 Million, Down 45%</span><br/><strong class=\"root-Tkn6WL2y\"><span>(20:52 GMT) </span></strong><span>Tourism Holdings Swings to Annual Loss on Impairments</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>By David Winning</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>SYDNEY--Recreational vehicle company Tourism Holdings reported a net lossfor a year marked by it moving into the takeover crosshairs of private equity.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Tourism Holdings reported a net loss of 25.8 million New Zealand dollars (US$15.1 million) for the 12 months through June, compared to a NZ$39.4 million profit a year earlier. The result was dragged down by NZ$54.5 million in one-off adjustments, mainly non-cash impairments of U.S. goodwill, and of U.S. and U.K. deferred tax assets.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>On an underlying basis, the company's profit totaled NZ$28.7 million, down 45%. It described these as \"bottom-of-the-cycle earnings.\" Annual revenue rose by 2% to NZ$937.2 million.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Directors of the company declared a final dividend of 4 New Zealand cents a share, bringing the full-year payout to 6.5 NZ cents.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Tourism Holdings faced significant headwinds in fiscal 2025 that made it vulnerable to a takeover bid. They included poor consumer confidence that hurt demand for recreational vehicles, along with geopolitical tensions and U.S. tariffs.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Earlier this month, Tourism Holdings rejected an offer worth some NZ$508.5 million from a consortium of BGH Capital and the family interests of Luke and Karl Trouchet as too low. The consortium made an all-cash proposal worth NZ$2.30 a share, but Tourism Holdings assesses the company is worth more than NZ$3.00 a share. The stock ended last week at NZ$2.20.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Tourism Holdings has outlined several initiatives that it hopes will improve performance. They include a possible sale of its U.K. and Ireland division, and reductions in overhead costs and inventory in Australia.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>On Monday, Tourism Holdings gave an assessment of the current business outlook, saying it expects global rental revenue to rise.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>\"This is supported by a forward rental book showing double-digit percentage revenue growth in all markets except the U.S.,\" the company said. \"Tourism Holdings also expects utilization improvements in all markets, while maintaining average yields.\"</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Still, Tourism Holdings is cautious about the outlook for its sales division, anticipating modest volume growth and broadly stable margins. Any material improvement is likely to incur from the 2026 calendar year, it said.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>\"A disciplined capital management approach is expected to result in substantially lower gross and net fleet capital expenditure compared to FY 2025, with fleet growth focused on ANZ,\" Tourism Holdings added.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Write to David Winning at david.winning@wsj.com</span></p></span></div></div>",
            "link": "https://www.tradingview.com/news/DJN_DN20250824000568:0/",
            "pub_date": "2025-08-25 04:52:00",
            "source": "Dow Jones Newswires",
            "kind": 1,
            "language": "en"
        },
        {
            "id": "DJN_DN20250824000530:0",
            "title": "Chorus Expects Earnings, Dividend to Rise in FY 2026",
            "description": "<div class=\"body-KX2tCBZq body-pIO_GYwT content-pIO_GYwT\"><div class=\"symbolsContainer-cBh_FN2P logosContainer-cwMMKgmm\" data-no-swipe=\"true\"></div><div><span><p class=\"\"><strong class=\"root-Tkn6WL2y\"><span>(20:30 GMT) </span></strong><span>*Chorus FY Net Profit NZ$4 Million</span><br/><strong class=\"root-Tkn6WL2y\"><span>(20:31 GMT) </span></strong><span>*Chorus FY Revenue NZ$1.01 Billion, Up 0.4%</span><br/><strong class=\"root-Tkn6WL2y\"><span>(20:31 GMT) </span></strong><span>*Chorus Final Dividend 34.5 New Zealand Cents/Share</span><br/><strong class=\"root-Tkn6WL2y\"><span>(20:32 GMT) </span></strong><span>*Chorus FY 2025 Ebitda NZ$705 Million</span><br/><strong class=\"root-Tkn6WL2y\"><span>(20:32 GMT) </span></strong><span>*Chorus Expects FY 2026 Ebitda NZ$710 Million-NZ$730 Million</span><br/><strong class=\"root-Tkn6WL2y\"><span>(20:32 GMT) </span></strong><span>*Chorus Expects FY 2026 Gross Capex NZ$375 Million-NZ$415 Million</span><br/><strong class=\"root-Tkn6WL2y\"><span>(20:32 GMT) </span></strong><span>*Chorus Expects FY 2026 Sustaining Capex NZ$195 Million-NZ$215 Million</span><br/><strong class=\"root-Tkn6WL2y\"><span>(20:33 GMT) </span></strong><span>*Chorus Expects FY 2026 Dividend 60 New Zealand Cents/Share</span><br/><strong class=\"root-Tkn6WL2y\"><span>(20:45 GMT) </span></strong><span>Chorus Expects Earnings, Dividend to Rise in FY 2026</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>By David Winning</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>SYDNEY--New Zealand telecommunications company Chorus forecast higher earnings in its new fiscal year, as it continues to move customers on to fiber connections ahead of the planned retirement of its copper network in urban areas.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Chorus said it expects earnings before interest, tax, depreciation and amortization--or Ebitda--of between 710 million New Zealand dollars (US$416.7 million) and NZ$730 million in the 12 months through June, 2026. Its Ebitda totaled NZ$705 million in fiscal 2025, at the lower end of guidance for NZ$700 million-NZ$720 million.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>The company expects to lift its dividend to 60 New Zealand cents a share, from 57.5 NZ cents in the just-ended period which included a final dividend of 34.5 NZ cents. Chorus has a policy of paying 70-90% of net operating cash flows, after sustaining capital expenditure.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Chorus also forecast sustaining capex of NZ$195 million-NZ$215 million.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Chorus provided this guidance alongside a statutory net profit of NZ$4 million for fiscal 2025, swinging from a loss of NZ$9 million a year ago. Annual revenue rose by 0.4% to NZ$1.01 billion, with fiber connections totaling around 1.12 million at the end of June.</span></p><p class=\"\"><span>Write to David Winning at david.winning@wsj.com</span></p></span></div></div>",
            "link": "https://www.tradingview.com/news/DJN_DN20250824000530:0/",
            "pub_date": "2025-08-25 04:45:00",
            "source": "Dow Jones Newswires",
            "kind": 1,
            "language": "en"
        },
